english:
  title: A Letter of Condolence to a Friend Upon the Loss of His Son
  author: Kang Hee-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I encountered you on the road yesterday evening and heard of your son's passing. I could not suppress my sudden grief. As you know, you held this child so dear—surely your heart is breaking unbearably. What can be done? What can be done?

    I have heard that since losing your son, tears fall with every word you speak, you have abandoned food and drink, and your mourning has exceeded all proper measure. Though such sorrow is natural to the human heart, this is not how we should mourn a young child, nor is it the way of one who truly cherishes himself. I have long known your kindness toward me, and I too have walked this sorrowful path. I dare now offer you a few thoughts that have brought me solace, and humbly ask that you consider them.

    When the sages established the rites, they always grounded them in human nature. Where feeling runs deep, the rites are also heightened. The bond between father and child is Heaven's decree—and yet, can the rites truly vary in their depth? For a young child taken too soon, we sorrow at death's cruelty; for one grown, we sorrow at misfortune. Yet grief's weight does not change with age, nor should the rites vary accordingly. And yet, for children who die young, there are three degrees of mourning garb, and the rites themselves diminish accordingly. Would the sages have done this without reason? The Record says: "When affection is deep, the mourning garb is heavy." Thus when affection is not paramount, the rites too must change. This is why the three categories of child mortality cannot bear the same rites as those for an adult.

    If the rites are not observed, then surely sorrow must be governed by discipline, not by passion alone. Long ago, Zixia lost his son and lost his sight from weeping. Zengzi came to offer condolences. Zixia said, "Heaven has no mercy—what sin have I committed?" Zengzi grew angry and said, "Shang! What do you mean you have no sin? You lost your son and lost your sight—that is your sin! How can you claim innocence?" Zixia threw down his staff and bowed, saying, "I was wrong, I was wrong. I have lived apart from the community for too long." Now Zixia walked among Confucius's disciples and learned from the sage himself; he was renowned for his learning and could not be said to be ignorant of ritual. His weeping for his son was natural, yet his grief became so extreme that it caused disease. Though he may have overstepped, we cannot simply condemn him as sinful. Yet Zengzi spoke harshly in anger, listing three transgressions without hesitation, and Zixia accepted his rebuke without anger. Why is the instruction between these sages so earnest? Because feeling must stop at ritual's boundary and not cross over. The death of one so lowly cannot trouble those of higher station.

    There was a man named Dongmen Wu of the state of Wei. When his son died, he did not grieve. His steward asked, "Your love for your son is unmatched in all the world. How is it that now he is dead, yet you do not grieve?" Dongmen Wu replied, "Did I not once have no son? When I had no son, I did not grieve. Now that my son is dead, it is as if I have no son again. Why should I grieve?" Though this reasoning seems detached, it shows wisdom in consoling oneself. Examining the ritual texts, we find no principle that physical decline should follow the death of a young child. Studying the words of the enlightened, even Dongmen Wu's teaching points this way. Why then do you not honor yourself? Why do you surrender to feeling and violate the rites to this extent?

    In the year Gyeongho, my firstborn daughter died of smallpox. At that time, though I tried to contain my grief, it ran deep. Whenever I saw a child on the road who resembled her, I could not help but weep. For this, my friends would mock me. Yet sorrow, once rooted, takes time to fade. Later, while still in mourning for her, I lost my youngest son. My feeling was no less deep, my pain no less sharp—yet I shed not a single tear, and sometimes I even forgot my sorrow. A month later, I spoke and laughed as before. Was I more compassionate then and cruel now?

    The difference is this: when my firstborn daughter died, both my parents still lived, my siblings were well, my household was whole and content—then suddenly came this blow. When my youngest died, I had already lost both parents, I was bereft until life's end, and I stood alone in this vast universe with nothing to lean upon. My heart itself was already broken, so I scarcely noticed fresh sorrows. Thus it is: when the heart is whole, even small griefs strike deeply; when the heart is already shattered, even great griefs touch it lightly. This is why you grieve so deeply for your young child, and why I scarcely grieved for my youngest.

    Long ago, Yannling Jizi of Wu traveled to Qi. On his return, his eldest son had died and was buried between Ying and Bo. Confucius said, "Jizi is a man of Wu versed in ritual. Let us go and observe." When the burial was complete, Jizi rolled up his left sleeve, turned his robe around, walked backward around the tomb, and cried out three times: "Flesh and bone return to earth—such is Fate! But the spirit knows no boundary, knows no boundary!" Then he departed. Confucius said, "Jizi's actions accord with ritual. Examining his words carefully, we see he understood the boundary between the visible and invisible worlds and grasped the true measure of mourning." Thus did the Master praise him.

    Your writings and deeds carry weight in this age. Your conduct must not falter. Moreover, both your parents are in good health, blessed with complete joy—do not let the death of one small child steal away your composure and cause you to neglect the filial duty of a cheerful countenance.

    Alas! Zixia's excessive grief that cost him his sight, Dongmen Wu's wisdom in consoling himself, Jizi's feelings refined by ritual—these are all expressions of father-child love. Surely you will choose the path that serves you best. I deeply wished to visit you, to discuss with you the nature of life's span, hoping you might find some comfort. But my own household has recently suffered from this very illness, and bound by common superstitions, I have not dared to visit. So I humbly set down these thoughts instead, hoping you will forgive my presumption and consider my words with kindness.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Zixia (子夏) was one of Confucius's foremost disciples, known for his scholarship and interpretation of texts.
  - key: ''
    value: Zengzi (曾子) was another of Confucius's most important disciples, celebrated for his filial piety and moral rigor.
  - key: ''
    value: The "Record" (禮記) refers to the Liji, a foundational Confucian text on ritual and propriety.
  - key: ''
    value: The three degrees of mourning garb (三殤) refer to ritual distinctions for children who die at different developmental stages.
  - key: ''
    value: Yannling Jizi (延陵季子), also known as Jizi of Wu, was a famous sage from the Spring and Autumn period, known for his observance of ritual propriety.
  - key: ''
    value: The author's reference to his own losses—first his daughter, then his youngest son, and later both parents—provides the experiential foundation for his counsel on grief and ritual.
  - key: ''
    value: '"Gyeongho" (庚午) likely refers to a year in the lunar calendar; the specific dating requires historical context.'
  - key: ''
    value: The concept of "complete joy" (具慶) refers to the blessing of having both parents alive and well.
